    81	- Gitea as the workers' actual git remote (10d follow-up).
    82	- Branch-protection requirement for the new job (deferred follow-up).
    83	- Multi-experiment / control-plane (Phase 12).
    84	- Kubernetes deployment (Phase 13).
    85	
    86	## Design
    87	
    88	### A. Test layout
    89	
    90	Two new files under `reference/compose/healthcheck/`:
    91	
    92	- **`e2e.sh`** — bash wrapper. Owns: tooling preflight, setup-experiment
    93	  invocation, staged `compose up -d`, dispatch to the python driver,
    94	  post-run event-log assertions via `jq`, termination drill, teardown.
    95	- **`e2e_drive.py`** — python driver. Owns: web UI sign-in, CSRF
    96	  extraction, planner-walkthrough claim/submit, admin-reclaim POST,
    97	  exit non-zero with diagnostic on assertion failure.
    98	
    99	The split is deliberate: bash is the natural shape for `compose` /
   100	`docker inspect` / `jq` plumbing; python is the natural shape for
   101	cookie-aware HTTP and form-CSRF round-tripping. Mirroring the existing
   102	smoke shells keeps the CI job shape uniform.
   103	
   104	### B. Bring-up sequence — the race-against-planner-host fix
   105	
   106	**Codex round-0 finding (blocker, addressed):** the scripted planner-host
   107	drains pending plan tasks in a tight loop on startup
   108	([`workers.py`](../../reference/packages/eden-dispatch/src/eden_dispatch/workers.py)).
   109	If the stack starts with planner-host running and the orchestrator
   110	seeds 4 plan tasks via `--plan-tasks 4`, the planner-host can claim
   111	all 4 before the python driver finishes signing in. So a "stop
   112	planner-host after up" pattern is fundamentally racy — the bad race
   113	is during initial startup, not steady state.
   114	
   115	**Fix:** start the stack *without* planner-host, run the UI
   116	walkthroughs against the seeded-but-unclaimed plan tasks while no
   117	planner-host is competing, then bring planner-host online:
   118	
   119	```bash
   120	# Stage 1: full stack minus planner-host. Compose's --wait + named
   121	# service-list interprets healthchecks for the listed services only;
   122	# none of them depend_on planner-host so this succeeds cleanly.
   123	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" up -d --wait \
   124	    --wait-timeout 240 \
   125	    postgres gitea blob-init \
   126	    task-store-server orchestrator \
   127	    implementer-host evaluator-host web-ui
   128	
   129	# orchestrator seeded plan-0001..plan-0004 at startup. None claimed.
   130	# Run python driver — claims plan-0001 (submit) and plan-0002
   131	# (admin-reclaim drill).
   132	
   133	python3 healthcheck/e2e_drive.py
   134	
   135	# Stage 2: bring planner-host online. It now picks up plan-0002
   136	# (returned to pending by admin-reclaim), plan-0003, and plan-0004.
   137	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" up -d \
   138	    --wait --wait-timeout 60 planner-host
   139	```
   140	
   141	**Note on `EDEN_PLAN_TASKS=4`:** the orchestrator's `--plan-tasks` flag
   142	defaults to 3 in the fixture. We override to 4 in `.env` so the four
   143	deterministic IDs `plan-0001..plan-0004` are seeded. The python driver
   144	uses two specific IDs (`plan-0001` for the submit walkthrough,
   145	`plan-0002` for the admin-reclaim drill); the other two go through the
   146	headless planner-host on the success path.
   147	
   148	```bash
   149	# After setup-experiment.sh writes .env, override:
   150	sed -i.bak 's/^EDEN_PLAN_TASKS=.*/EDEN_PLAN_TASKS=4/' "$ENV_FILE"
   151	rm -f "${ENV_FILE}.bak"
   152	```
   153	
   154	The `sed -i.bak` form is GNU/BSD-portable (BSD `sed -i ''` rejects
   155	the bare `-i`; GNU `sed -i.bak` accepts it identically).
   156	
   157	**Confirmed plan-task ID shape** ([`orchestrator/cli.py:116`](../../reference/services/orchestrator/src/eden_orchestrator/cli.py)):
   158	numeric `--plan-tasks N` expands to `plan-0001..plan-{N:04d}`. So
   159	with `N=4` we have exactly `plan-0001`, `plan-0002`, `plan-0003`,
   160	`plan-0004`.
   161	
   162	### C. Web UI planner walkthrough — actual route shapes
   163	
   164	The python driver against `localhost:${WEB_UI_HOST_PORT:-8090}`:
   165	
   166	```python
   167	# 1. Sign in (no body needed; chunk-9b auth stub is a no-questions form)
   168	resp = ui.post("/signin", follow_redirects=False)
   169	assert resp.status_code == 303
   170	
   171	# 2. GET /planner/ — list pending plan tasks, scrape CSRF token
   172	resp = ui.get("/planner/")
   173	assert resp.status_code == 200
   174	assert "plan-0001" in resp.text  # the seeded task is visible
   175	csrf = re.search(r'name="csrf_token"\s+value="([^"]+)"', resp.text).group(1)
   176	
   177	# 3. Claim plan-0001
   178	resp = ui.post(
   179	    "/planner/plan-0001/claim",
   180	    content=urlencode({"csrf_token": csrf}),
   181	    headers={"content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
   182	    follow_redirects=False,
   183	)
   184	assert resp.status_code == 303
   185	
   186	# 4. GET /planner/plan-0001/draft — re-scrape CSRF (form re-rendered)
   187	resp = ui.get("/planner/plan-0001/draft")
   188	assert resp.status_code == 200
   189	csrf = re.search(r'name="csrf_token"\s+value="([^"]+)"', resp.text).group(1)
   190	
   191	# 5. POST /planner/plan-0001/submit — note: returns 200 with rendered
   192	#    success template, NOT 303 (codex round-0 fix).
   193	body = urlencode([
   194	    ("csrf_token", csrf),
   195	    ("status", "success"),
   196	    ("slug", "e2e-feat"),
   197	    ("priority", "1.0"),
   198	    ("parent_commits", base_sha),  # from $EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA in env
   199	    ("rationale", "## why\n\nbecause."),
   200	])
   201	resp = ui.post(
   202	    "/planner/plan-0001/submit",
   203	    content=body,
   204	    headers={"content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
   205	)
   206	assert resp.status_code == 200
   207	assert "submitted" in resp.text.lower()
   208	```
   209	
   210	The submit form fields match
   211	[`reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/forms.py`](../../reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/forms.py):
   212	slug regex `[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+`, priority parsed via `float()`,
   213	`parent_commits` comma-split with each entry validated as a 40-hex SHA.
   214	`base_sha` comes from `$EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA` (read from `.env` and
   215	passed through to the python driver via env).
   216	
   217	### D. Admin-reclaim drill — actual redirect URL
   218	
   219	The python driver, in the same httpx session:
   220	
   221	```python
   222	# Claim plan-0002 — same shape as plan-0001 above, but no submit
   223	csrf = ...  # re-scrape from /planner/
   224	resp = ui.post(
   225	    "/planner/plan-0002/claim",
   226	    content=urlencode({"csrf_token": csrf}),
   227	    headers={"content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
   228	    follow_redirects=False,
   229	)
   230	assert resp.status_code == 303
   231	
   232	# Verify it's listed under claimed
   233	resp = ui.get("/admin/tasks/?state=claimed")
   234	assert resp.status_code == 200
   235	assert "plan-0002" in resp.text
   236	
   237	# Re-scrape CSRF from the admin task-detail page (the reclaim form is
   238	# rendered on /admin/tasks/<id>/, not the list page)
   239	resp = ui.get("/admin/tasks/plan-0002/")
   240	csrf = re.search(r'name="csrf_token"\s+value="([^"]+)"', resp.text).group(1)
   241	
   242	# POST reclaim — codex-confirmed redirect URL has the trailing slash:
   243	# /admin/tasks/<id>/?reclaimed=ok (NOT /admin/tasks/<id>?reclaimed=ok)
   244	resp = ui.post(
   245	    "/admin/tasks/plan-0002/reclaim",
   246	    content=urlencode({"csrf_token": csrf}),
   247	    headers={"content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
   248	    follow_redirects=False,
   249	)
   250	assert resp.status_code == 303
   251	assert resp.headers["location"] == "/admin/tasks/plan-0002/?reclaimed=ok"
   252	```
   253	
   254	[`admin.py:331`](../../reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/routes/admin.py)
   255	confirms the trailing-slash form.
   256	
   257	### E. Event-log read-back
   258	
   259	`task-store-server` is internal-only — no published host port. The
   260	python driver cannot read events directly; the post-walkthrough
   261	`task.reclaimed` assertion runs from `e2e.sh` via `compose exec`,
   262	exactly the way `smoke.sh` already does:
   263	
   264	```bash
   265	EVENTS_JSON="$(
   266	    docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" \
   267	        exec -T task-store-server \
   268	        curl -fsS \
   269	            -H "Authorization: Bearer ${EDEN_SHARED_TOKEN}" \
   270	            -H "X-Eden-Experiment-Id: ${EXPERIMENT_ID}" \
   271	            "http://localhost:8080/v0/experiments/${EXPERIMENT_ID}/events"
   272	)"
   273	
   274	RECLAIMED_OPERATOR="$(
   275	    echo "$EVENTS_JSON" \
   276	        | jq '(.events // .) | [.[] | select(
   277	              .type == "task.reclaimed"
   278	              and .data.cause == "operator"
   279	            )] | length'
   280	)"
   281	test "$RECLAIMED_OPERATOR" -ge 1
   282	```
   283	
   284	### F. Quiescence wait — same as smoke
   285	
   286	After the python driver returns success and `e2e.sh` brings
   287	planner-host online, wait up to 240s for `eden-orchestrator` to enter
   288	`exited` status with code 0, exactly as `smoke.sh` does. Bumped from
   289	smoke's 180s because:
   290	
   291	- 4 plan tasks (vs 3 in smoke) → ~33% more work
   292	- The admin-reclaimed task is dispatched twice (once → claimed → back
   293	  to pending → dispatched again), adding small extra work
   294	
   295	### G. End-state assertions (complete set)
   296	
   297	```bash
   298	# Same shape as smoke.sh, adjusted arithmetic:
   299	test "$TRIAL_INTEGRATED" -ge 4         # 4 plan -> 4 trials (1 proposal each)
   300	test "$TASK_COMPLETED"   -ge 12        # 4 plan + 4 implement + 4 evaluate
   301	test "$PLAN_COMPLETED"   -ge 4         # all 4 plan tasks reach terminal
   302	
   303	# Phase-10e additional invariant:
   304	test "$RECLAIMED_OPERATOR" -ge 1       # the admin-reclaim drill produced one
   305	```
   306	
   307	### H. Termination drill — full container set
   308	
   309	**Codex round-0 finding (medium, addressed):** the original drill
   310	narrowed to `eden-*` containers, missing `eden-postgres`, `eden-gitea`,
   311	and `eden-blob-init`. Also: `eden-repo-init` ran via
   312	`compose run --rm --no-deps` and is gone by termination time
   313	([`setup-experiment.sh:251`](../../reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh)).
   314	
   315	The drill operates over the actual `compose ps -a` output:
   316	
   317	```bash
   318	echo "--- termination drill: stop with 10s budget ---"
   319	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" stop --timeout 10
   320	
   321	# Iterate every container compose still knows about, regardless of
   322	# name pattern. This naturally covers postgres, gitea, blob-init,
   323	# task-store-server, orchestrator, planner-host, implementer-host,
   324	# evaluator-host, and web-ui. eden-repo-init is gone (--rm) so it
   325	# does not appear.
   326	for name in $(
   327	    docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" ps -a \
   328	        --format '{{.Name}}'
   329	); do
   330	    status="$(docker inspect --format '{{.State.Status}}' "$name")"
   331	    code="$(docker inspect --format '{{.State.ExitCode}}' "$name")"
   332	    test "$status" = "exited" || {
   333	        echo "$name still in status $status after stop --timeout 10" >&2
   334	        exit 1
   335	    }
   336	    test "$code" != "137" || {
   337	        echo "$name was SIGKILLed (exit code 137)" >&2
   338	        docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$ENV_FILE" \
   339	            logs --tail 30 "$name" >&2
   340	        exit 1
   341	    }
   342	    # blob-init is a one-shot that already exited 0 during bring-up;
   343	    # this is just a paranoia check, not a status-change.
   344	done
   345	```
   346	
   347	**Why `!= 137` instead of `== 0`:**
   348	[`reference/services/_common/`](../../reference/services/_common/)'s
   349	SIGTERM handler exits the EDEN python services cleanly with code 0
   350	(verified by codex against
   351	[`web-ui cli.py:155`](../../reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/cli.py),
   352	[`task-store cli.py:171`](../../reference/services/task-store-server/src/eden_task_store_server/cli.py),
   353	[`planner cli.py:109`](../../reference/services/planner/src/eden_planner_host/cli.py),
   354	[`implementer cli.py:85`](../../reference/services/implementer/src/eden_implementer_host/cli.py),
   355	[`evaluator cli.py:90`](../../reference/services/evaluator/src/eden_evaluator_host/cli.py)).
   356	But postgres / gitea use external images we don't control; if a future
   357	upstream tweak changes their default SIGTERM handler to default-handler
   358	(producing 143), `== 0` would falsely fail. `!= 137` captures the only
   359	thing we actually care about: **the container did NOT need SIGKILL**.
   360	
   361	### I. Teardown
   362	
   363	`e2e.sh`'s `cleanup()` trap runs `docker compose down -v` on EXIT,
   364	exactly as smoke.sh does. The termination drill's `compose stop` does
   365	NOT call `down -v` itself — that would lose the volumes before the
   366	drill verifies anything. `down -v` is the trap's responsibility;
   367	`stop` is the drill's.
   368	
   369	### J. CI wiring
   370	
   371	Add `compose-e2e` to `.github/workflows/ci.yml` mirroring
   372	`compose-smoke-subprocess`:
   373	
   374	```yaml
   375	compose-e2e:
   376	  name: compose-e2e
   377	  runs-on: ubuntu-latest
   378	  timeout-minutes: 20  # 5 more than smoke jobs to absorb the drill
   379	  steps:
   380	    - uses: actions/checkout@v4
   381	    - name: Verify docker compose + jq + python3 are available
   382	      run: |
   383	        docker compose version
   384	        jq --version
   385	        python3 --version
   386	    - name: Install python driver deps
   387	      run: pip install 'httpx>=0.27,<1'
   388	    - name: Run compose e2e
   389	      working-directory: reference/compose
   390	      run: bash healthcheck/e2e.sh
   391	```
   392	
   393	**httpx pin** is `>=0.27,<1` (codex round-0 fix), matching the
   394	workspace's existing pin in
   395	[`eden-wire/pyproject.toml:8`](../../reference/packages/eden-wire/pyproject.toml)
   396	and
   397	[`_common/pyproject.toml:8`](../../reference/services/_common/pyproject.toml).
   398	A bare `pip install` is lighter than wiring up the full `uv sync` —
   399	the CI job only needs the python driver to talk HTTP, no workspace
   400	imports.
   401	
   402	### K. Failure-mode handling (revised)
   403	
   404	| Failure | Surface | Recovery |
   405	|---|---|---|
   406	| `compose up --wait` (stage 1) times out on a service | bash exits non-zero | trap dumps `compose ps -a` + `compose logs --tail 30` for unhealthy services; teardown |
   407	| Python driver: claim returns no eligible task | driver exits non-zero with diagnostic naming the task IDs it tried | trap dumps `compose logs task-store-server`; teardown |
   408	| Python driver: planner submit returns non-200 | driver exits non-zero with the response status + body excerpt | trap dumps `compose logs web-ui`; teardown |
   409	| Python driver: admin-reclaim CSRF rejected | response is bare 403 (per [`admin.py:317`](../../reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/routes/admin.py)); driver exits with diagnostic — indicates a CSRF-extraction bug in the driver | shell trap dumps body; teardown |
   410	| Python driver: admin-reclaim 303 to `?error=…` instead of `?reclaimed=ok` | driver exits with the error-banner code | trap dumps `compose logs web-ui`; teardown |
   411	| `compose up planner-host` (stage 2) fails healthcheck | planner-host has no healthcheck so this is just `compose up -d` succeeding when the container is started; no race | not applicable |
   412	| Orchestrator doesn't quiesce in 240s | bash exits non-zero | trap dumps `compose logs --tail 60 orchestrator planner-host implementer-host evaluator-host`; teardown |
   413	| End-state assertion fails (counts low) | bash exits non-zero with the failed comparison | trap dumps `compose logs --tail 60 orchestrator`; teardown |
   414	| Container SIGKILLed during stop (exit code 137) | bash exits non-zero in the termination loop | trap dumps `compose logs --tail 30 <name>` for the offending container; teardown |
   415	
   416	The **TTL-expiry concern** flagged in round-0 is moot: the web-ui's
   417	`--claim-ttl-seconds` default is **3600** (1 hour) per
   418	[`reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/cli.py:53`](../../reference/services/web-ui/src/eden_web_ui/cli.py),
   419	and the admin-reclaim drill runs in <5s after the claim. No new flag
   420	is needed.

