   421	
   422	### L. Deterministic bring-up choreography
   423	
   424	With the staged `compose up -d` (stage 1 omits planner-host, stage 2
   425	adds it), the only competitor for plan-task claims during the UI
   426	walkthrough is the chunk-1 expired-claim sweeper running inside the
   427	orchestrator. The sweeper only reclaims claims that have aged past
   428	their TTL; with the web-ui claim aged ~1s and the TTL set to 3600s,
   429	the sweeper is a no-op for the drill's window. So the choreography is
   430	deterministic.
   431	
   432	**One subtle point:** the orchestrator seeds plan tasks before
   433	returning from its startup phase. By the time `compose up --wait` for
   434	stage 1 succeeds (orchestrator container `running`), the seed has
   435	already completed. The python driver's `GET /admin/tasks/?kind=plan`
   436	will see all 4 in `pending`. There is no startup-time race between
   437	"orchestrator finished seeding" and "driver reads tasks" because the
   438	healthcheck-based `--wait` for orchestrator (it doesn't have a
   439	healthcheck) is satisfied as soon as the container is `running`,
   440	which is after seeding completes. Verify this empirically during impl
   441	review; if it's racy, add a small `sleep 2` before invoking the python
   442	driver.
   443	
   444	Actually — let me check: orchestrator has no healthcheck (looking at
   445	the compose.yaml). So `compose up --wait` for orchestrator just means
   446	"container is running." If the orchestrator process is slow to seed,
   447	the driver could read an empty list. **Mitigation in the python
   448	driver:** poll `GET /admin/tasks/?kind=plan` for up to 30s waiting
   449	for all 4 IDs to appear, before starting the walkthrough. This avoids
   450	the small-but-real startup race without requiring an arbitrary sleep.
   451	
   452	## Tests / verification
   453	
   454	This chunk's deliverable IS a test (compose-e2e). There are no new
   455	unit tests. The verification path is:
   456	
   457	1. `bash reference/compose/healthcheck/e2e.sh` passes locally
   458	2. `compose-e2e` job goes green on CI for the PR
   459	3. The existing `compose-smoke` and `compose-smoke-subprocess` jobs
   460	   still pass (no regressions to the base smoke shape)
   461	4. All other CI jobs (markdown, schema, ruff, pyright, pytest,
   462	   schema-parity, python-test-postgres) still green
